      ESG Aramco
   =20
 =20

If I tell you that Company X is an oil company, you probably assume that it=
 creates a lot of carbon emissions. Drilling for oil is dirty work, but als=
o the ultimate=C2=A0users=C2=A0of the oil will burn it and create a lot of =
emissions, and it seems reasonable to attribute those emissions to Company =
X. If it didn=E2=80=99t drill the oil, they wouldn=E2=80=99t burn the oil. =
Maybe they would burn some other oil? But that=E2=80=99s not the point. The=
 point is that most people associate oil companies with carbon emissions, p=
retty reasonably. And so, for instance, environmental, social and governanc=
e-focused (ESG) investors might lower the carbon impact of their portfolios=
 by not investing in=C2=A0oil companies.
If I tell you that Company Y is an investment firm, you probably=C2=A0assum=
e that it does not itself do a lot of carbon emissions. It=E2=80=99s some p=
eople, some desks, some computers. It uses electricity, and its employees p=
robably take business trips on airplanes, but no more than most companies. =
If you care about carbon emissions, you=C2=A0might ask questions like =E2=
=80=9Cis Company Y an ESG investment firm?=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cdoes Compan=
y Y do a lot of investing in coal companies?=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cwhat are =
the total carbon emissions of the companies in Company Y=E2=80=99s portfoli=
o?=E2=80=9D; you might want to get a broader sense of Company Y=E2=80=99s c=
ontribution to carbon emissions beyond the amount of carbon that it uses in=
 its own operations.
But you =E2=80=A6=C2=A0might =E2=80=A6=C2=A0not? At some point the accounti=
ng has to stop. If you are, for instance, yourself an ESG fund manager, and=
 your mandate is to buy bonds of companies that don=E2=80=99t do a lot of c=
arbon emissions and to avoid bonds of companies that do do a lot of carbon =
emissions, you might have a simpler checklist. Oil companies: bad, no, don=
=E2=80=99t buy their bonds. Investment firms: fine, yes, not a problem, whe=
ther they are ESG investment firms or regular investment firms or even coal=
-focused investment firms.
But investment firms are, in a sense, free. An investment firm is a company=
 whose business is owning securities; you can create companies easily,=C2=
=A0and you can turn anything into a security. You can take a bunch of real =
assets =E2=80=94=C2=A0pipelines, oil wells, whatever =E2=80=94=C2=A0and put=
 them into a company, and then that company can issue securities to another=
 company, and=C2=A0that second=C2=A0company doesn=E2=80=99t own any pipelin=
es or oil wells or whatever;=C2=A0that=C2=A0company just owns securities. I=
t=E2=80=99s just an investment=C2=A0firm! Totally clean.=C2=A0
There is   a hilarious arbitrage:

Saudi Aramco, the world=E2=80=99s largest oil company, has become an unlike=
ly beneficiary of funds earmarked for sustainable investments thanks to a c=
omplex web of financial structures it used to raise money from its pipeline=
s.=C2=A0=E2=80=A6
The unlikely tie-up between Aramco and ESG began with the creation of two s=
ubsidiaries =E2=80=94 the Aramco Oil Pipelines Company and the Aramco Gas P=
ipelines Company. Aramco sold 49% of the shares in each unit to consortiums=
 led by EIG Global Energy Partners LLC and BlackRock Inc., respectively. Th=
ese investors used bridge loans from banks to fund those transactions.=C2=
=A0
In order to generate cash to repay the bank loans, the EIG and BlackRock co=
nsortiums created two special purpose vehicles: EIG Pearl Holdings and Gree=
nSaif Pipelines Bidco, both registered at the same Luxembourg address. Thes=
e SPVs then sold bonds, which, since they had no direct links to the fossil=
-fuel industry, ended up getting an above-average score in a widely-used JP=
Morgan Chase & Co. sustainability screening based on third-party ESG scores=
.=C2=A0
From there, the bonds made their way into JPMorgan=E2=80=99s ESG indexes, w=
hich are cumulatively tracked by about $40 billion of assets under manageme=
nt. Investors in the SPV bonds include funds managed by UBS Group AG, Legal=
 & General Investment Management and the investment arm of HSBC Holdings Pl=
c.=C2=A0

You can do this with anything! Absolutely anything:
=09Horrible Coal Inc. wants to raise money.=09It sets up a special purpose =
vehicle, Hypertechnical Investments Ltd.=09Horrible Coal issues bonds to Hy=
pertechnical Investments.=09Hypertechnical issues its own bonds to ESG fund=
s: =E2=80=9CWe are just a little old investment firm, just two traders and =
two computers, no carbon emissions here! And our credit is very good, becau=
se we have no other liabilities and our assets are all investment-grade bon=
ds. =E2=80=98Which investment-grade bonds,=E2=80=99 did you ask? Sorry, I=
=E2=80=99m not sure I heard you right, you=E2=80=99re breaking up. Anyway w=
e=E2=80=99ll look=C2=A0for your check, bye!=E2=80=9D

Though my made-up names are silly, and in the actual Aramco case one of the=
 not-an-oil-company=C2=A0SPVs is named =E2=80=9CGreenSaif=C2=A0Pipelines Bi=
dco.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CPipelines=E2=80=9D is right in the name! The only wa=
y you would think that GreenSaif Pipelines Bidco =E2=80=9Chad no direct lin=
ks to the fossil-fuel industry=E2=80=9D is if (1) you started reading the n=
ame but stopped after you got to the =E2=80=9CGreen=E2=80=9D part (plausibl=
e!) or (2) you never read the name at all, never thought about it, just loo=
ked at the balance sheet and saw only shares of stock, not pipelines or oil=
 wells, and said =E2=80=9Cah, stock, well, that=E2=80=99s green enough.=E2=
=80=9D

