      Elsewhere in ESG
   =20
 =20

Well, this is  not an=C2=A0unrelated=C2=A0mechanism:

Climate activists and Wall Street are making it tougher for Big Oil to stay=
 in the oil business. They=E2=80=99ve also helped make Jeffery Hildebrand a=
 multibillionaire.
Hildebrand, who is little known outside his hometown of Houston, has become=
 one of America=E2=80=99s largest independent drillers by buying assets on =
the cheap, cutting costs and then squeezing out both oil and profit from we=
lls that others left for dead. =E2=80=A6
It=E2=80=99s a business model that is growing from a niche into a juggernau=
t as the industry=E2=80=99s giants, facing mounting calls to cut their carb=
on emissions, dial back on drilling and shed assets. Hilcorp is privately h=
eld so it doesn=E2=80=99t face ESG demands=E2=80=94short for environmental,=
 social and governance issues=E2=80=94from investors. That means the pressu=
re on big oil companies isn=E2=80=99t necessarily leading to less pumping, =
but rather pumping by less-accountable players.=C2=A0
Hilcorp has become a natural clearinghouse for big oil companies looking to=
 unload aging wells that may leak copious amounts of methane, a powerful at=
mosphere-warming gas.=C2=A0...
Between 2017 and 2021, companies with methane-reduction goals sold $115.6 b=
illion worth of assets to firms that don=E2=80=99t have explicit targets fo=
r reduction, the Environmental Defense Fund said in a report last year.
Over that same period, Hilcorp bought more than $9 billion worth of assets =
from companies including an Exxon Mobil affiliate, ConocoPhillips and BP, a=
ccording to a tally by energy analytics firm Enverus.

My general model of ESG and carbon emissions goes something like this:
=09ESG investors raise the cost of capital of carbon-emitting projects, by =
refusing to invest in companies with excessive emissions, or by investing i=
n those companies but pressuring their executives to get rid of the most ca=
rbon-emitting assets.=09One effect of this is to cause public companies to =
get rid of their most carbon-emitting assets, to lower their cost of capita=
l (and avoid pressure from shareholders).=09Another effect=C2=A0is to cause=
 the=C2=A0buyers=C2=A0of these assets to have   a higher cost of capital an=
d thus=C2=A0a shorter time horizon:=C2=A0If your cost of capital is high, t=
hen a dollar today is worth more than a dollar in 10 years, so you will pum=
p all the oil now.=09Another effect is to cause the buyers of those assets =
to systematically=C2=A0care less about emissions=C2=A0than the sellers: If =
you care a lot about emissions (because you have ESG-focused shareholders a=
nd are trying to meet ESG goals), you will do what you can to limit emissio=
ns from whatever assets you own, but if you are explicitly in the business =
of buying everyone else=E2=80=99s most carbon-emitting assets then you are =
not going to get any ESG credit and so might as well go nuts on the emissio=
ns.=09Another effect is to cause the buyers of those assets=C2=A0to get ric=
h: =E2=80=9CThe cost of capital of aging oil wells is high=E2=80=9D   is an=
other way of saying =E2=80=9Cthe expected return=C2=A0on equity of owning a=
ging oil wells is high.=E2=80=9D

This story is all of those things.

 =20
   =20
      Indexes
   =20
 =20

We   talked a bit yesterday about how=C2=A0Nasdaq Inc. plans to adjust its =
Nasdaq 100 index of big tech companies to reduce the impact of the very big=
gest tech companies. This will have the effect of making the index a bit mo=
re representative of the broad tech sector, as my colleague   John Authers =
explains, but it has the=C2=A0purpose=C2=A0of helping index funds linked to=
 the Nasdaq 100 be in compliance with US Securities and Exchange Commission=
 and Internal Revenue Service rules about diversification. Those rules basi=
cally require funds to have no more than 50% of their assets in stocks that=
 each make up more than 5% of their assets; currently the Nasdaq 100 is som=
ewhat uncomfortably close to that cap, so it is going to lower the weights =
of its biggest stocks to give index funds more breathing room.
Here is Nasdaq=E2=80=99s  published methodology for re-weighting the Nasdaq=
 100. Basically the method is:
=09Weight the stocks in the index by market capitalization to get initial w=
eights.=09=E2=80=9CIf the aggregate weight of the subset of issuers whose S=
tage 1 weights exceed 4.5% does not exceed 48%, Stage 1 weights are used as=
 final weights.=E2=80=9D If not, then =E2=80=9Cthe aggregate weight of the =
subset of issuers whose Stage 1 weights exceed 4.5% is set to 40%.=E2=80=9D=
=C2=A0

This has a curious little effect. If the stocks with greater-than-4.5% init=
ial weights add up to=C2=A0significantly=C2=A0more than 40%, they will all =
be cut back a lot
  [1]
: If there are 10 stocks that would each make up 6% of the index by market =
cap (60% total), then this method would cut them each back by one-third, to=
 4% each (40% total, the Stage 2 cap). And this would mean that stocks with=
 less-than-4.5% initial weights would be increased significantly: If the 10=
 big stocks get cut back from 60% of the index to 40%, then the 90 smaller =
stocks each have to have their weights go up by 50% (from 40% total to 60%)=
 to make up for it.
If each of those 90 small stocks made up 0.44% of the index by market cap, =
they=E2=80=99d each increase to 0.66% as the big stocks got cut back. But i=
f one of those small stocks made up, say, 4.49% of the index by market cap,=
 then I=C2=A0think=C2=A0that its weighting would also increase, in Stage 2,=
 to about 6.7% of the index. This seems kind of=C2=A0wrong=C2=A0=E2=80=94=
=C2=A0it sort of defeats the purpose of the adjustment
  [2]
=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0and perhaps Nasdaq would avoid it, by capping the Stag=
e 2 weights rather than doing everything pro rata. But the methodology does=
 seem to suggest that the weighting of almost-but-not-quite 4.5% stocks wou=
ld go up in the adjustment, possibly to above 5%.
This would mean that, in this adjustment, a stock that is just more than 4.=
5% of the market capitalization of the Nasdaq 100 would lose a lot of weigh=
t in the index, while a stock that is just less than 4.5% would gain a lot =
of weight in the index.
Nasdaq=E2=80=99s  announcement says that the =E2=80=9Crebalance of the inde=
x will be enacted based on the index securities and shares outstanding as o=
f July 3, 2023.=E2=80=9D Here are the weightings of the biggest stocks in t=
he=C2=A0index as of July 3, from Bloomberg
  [3]
:


   =20

Notice that there is one stock that is just above 4.5%, and it is Tesla. No=
tice that there is one stock that is just below 4.5%, and it is Meta. The t=
op six companies (Microsoft, Apple, Alphabet, Nvidia, Amazon and Tesla) are=
 all above 4.5%, and they add up to 50.9% of the index; the reweighting wou=
ld cut them back to 40%, a 21% decrease. Meanwhile the=C2=A0other=C2=A0stoc=
ks in the index would see their weightings go up by 22%.
Tesla would, on my math, go from being 4.5% of the index to being 2.8%. Met=
a would, on my math, go from being 4.2% to being 5.1%. It seems that the Na=
sdaq rebalance will cause investors to=C2=A0sell Tesla=C2=A0and=C2=A0buy Me=
ta.=C2=A0
I should say that I am not at all confident of this: This would be kind of =
a silly result, bringing Meta above 5% of the index and arbitrarily flippin=
g its position with Tesla,
  [4]
=C2=A0and it=E2=80=99s entirely possible that the actual adjustment will no=
t work this way. (=E2=80=9CThe index share announcements and pro-forma file=
 release will take place July 14,=E2=80=9D  says Nasdaq, so I guess we will=
 know then.)=C2=A0
But this seems to be the market assumption. The top six companies=C2=A0on t=
hat list were all down a bit between Friday=E2=80=99s rebalancing announcem=
ent and yesterday=E2=80=99s close; Meta was up 2.7% over that time, though =
it has had other news. And a JPMorgan Global Quantitative and Derivatives S=
trategy note on Monday estimated that =E2=80=9Cthe expected turnover for th=
e index is about 22% (two way), which will trigger $62 billion in trading n=
otional from passive trackers,=E2=80=9D and that Tesla will see outflows of=
 about $2.7 billion to $3 billion while Meta will see inflows of about $2 b=
illion.=C2=A0
I mention this mostly because it is weird,
  [5]
=C2=A0but also a little bit because Mark Zuckerberg and Elon Musk are engag=
ed in a series of very strange competitions these days, and this is a funny=
 little win for Zuckerberg.

 =20
   =20
      Pitches
   =20
 =20

The way I thought of the boom in private tech companies in the late 2010s w=
as that there was a lot of global capital available to be invested in tech =
companies, and relatively few tech ideas and entrepreneurs that could plaus=
ibly achieve global scale. Entrepreneurs were in demand, capital was cheap =
and plentiful, and so you got not only enormous valuations but also very fo=
under-friendly terms for big private tech investments.
In 2023 it seems somehow appropriate that there is a glut of private equity=
 firms and a shortage of plumbers. Bloomberg=E2=80=99s=C2=A0Michael Sasso r=
eports:

Local plumbers and lumber-yard owners across the US are feeling a bit like =
tech entrepreneurs of late =E2=80=94 juggling multiple offers from private =
equity-backed firms that increasingly are targeting mom-and-pop businesses.=
=C2=A0
Wall Street has been buying into fragmented Main Street industries for year=
s, with dental and veterinary practices among the favorite targets. It=E2=
=80=99s known as the roll-up strategy =E2=80=93 and it=E2=80=99s catching a=
 tailwind right now, and expanding rapidly in household services and buildi=
ng materials. ...
In the Atlanta area, Jay Cunningham says he gets several pitches a week fro=
m PE-backed firms wanting to buy his Superior Plumbing =E2=80=94 one of the=
 few sizeable local firms that hasn=E2=80=99t already been snapped up by in=
vestors =E2=80=94 or from investment bankers wanting to bring Superior to m=
arket. He=E2=80=99s not interested.
=E2=80=9CI probably think they=E2=80=99re a nuisance as a whole,=E2=80=9D C=
unningham says. =E2=80=A6
John Loud
  [6]
=C2=A0gets as many as 30 solicitations a month for his Kennesaw, Georgia-ba=
sed alarm installation firm, Loud Security Systems, which has about 60 empl=
oyees and more than $7 million in annual revenue.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s a non-stop barrage,=E2=80=9D Loud says, and it=E2=80=
=99s been going on for years. He used to joke with employees: =E2=80=9CIf y=
ou want job security, save me from these calls and these emails.=E2=80=9D=
=C2=A0

There=E2=80=99s a business idea there. You start a=C2=A0middle-market inves=
tment bank=C2=A0and you go out to small businesses saying =E2=80=9Cfor a $1=
,000 annual retainer, you can send=C2=A0every investment firm who contacts =
you a form email saying that I am your investment banker and they should wo=
rk through me, and then I will put their pitches in the garbage so you don=
=E2=80=99t have to.=E2=80=9D
  [7]
 PE-Be-Gone. Surely there are a few thousand clients who=E2=80=99d want tha=
t; here are two, anyway.
Sasso notes some economic factors driving private equity to spend more on r=
oll-ups=C2=A0(plumbing is relatively recession-proof, small private compani=
es are cheaper, public ones are too averse to selling at below-peak valuati=
ons). But the deep supply-and-demand story there might be something like =
=E2=80=9CUS society pushes young people into college rather than the trades=
, and then colleges push ambitious students=C2=A0into private equity, and t=
he result is that we have way too many private equity investors and way too=
 few plumbers.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0

 =20
   =20
      Meetings
   =20
 =20

This is   kind of cool I guess:

Time is money, and Shopify Inc. wants its workers to understand that maxim =
applies to pointless meetings, too.=C2=A0
The Canadian e-commerce company has rolled out a calculator embedded in emp=
loyees=E2=80=99 calendar app that estimates the cost of any meeting with th=
ree or more people. The tool uses average compensation data across roles an=
d disciplines, along with meeting length and attendee count, to put a price=
 tag on the event. A typical 30 minute endeavor with three employees can ru=
n from $700 up to $1,600. Adding an executive =E2=80=94 like Chief Operatin=
g Officer Kaz Nejatian, who built the program during a company-wide hack da=
y =E2=80=94 can shoot the cost above $2,000. ...
=E2=80=9CNo one at Shopify would expense a $500 dinner,=E2=80=9D Nejatian s=
aid in an interview. =E2=80=9CBut lots and lots of people spend way more th=
an that in meetings without ever making a decision. The goal of this thing =
is to show you that time is money. If you have to spend it, you think about=
 it.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0

You can take that too literally, though. Nothing you do at work is free,=C2=
=A0everything has a time cost, and most people cannot spend 40 hours a week=
 shipping impeccable products. If you quantify the time cost of meetings, y=
ou will get fewer meetings, but if you quantify=C2=A0only=C2=A0the time cos=
t of meetings and not of anything else, you might=C2=A0get a below-optimal =
amount of meetings, as people replace expensive-seeming meetings with free-=
seeming substitutes. If meetings are expensive but emails are free, some co=
nversations that should be meetings will be interminable email threads.
One=C2=A0funny solution would be embedding the cost calculator in=C2=A0all=
=C2=A0of the employees=E2=80=99 apps, not just the calendar one.
  [8]
=C2=A0Write an email and the cost of your time ticks up every second. Read =
Money Stuff on your browser with a little price tag next to it increasing e=
very second. Slack Nejatian and get a bill for it. Call him on the phone, g=
et a bill. At the next hack day, you build an artificial-intelligence tool =
to estimate the most cost-effective way to discuss anything, given the subj=
ect matter and the people involved, so you can choose between meetings and =
emails and Slacks and phone calls in a way that minimizes your bill.
Elsewhere in workplace productivity, people who work from home have discove=
red the benefits of  working around other people:

Consultant Micha Goebig scrolled through her phone to find receipts and bil=
l clients while on her home computer on Friday afternoon. Nine strangers qu=
ietly watched her on a video link while also doing their own solo work.
The small group was gathered online by Flow Club, a subscription service th=
at says it can help home-based workers stay on task and be productive by qu=
ietly working in tandem. The online session was built around body doubling,=
 a productivity strategy gaining traction among remote and hybrid employees=
 who say they get more done if others are looking on. =E2=80=A6
Other companies also offer virtual co-working arrangements via a subscripti=
on. Flow Club charges between $33 and $40 a month for access to over 100 da=
ily body-doubling sessions that are capped at 10 people and end with a cele=
bratory burst of confetti on the screen. For $7 to $10 a month, Focusmate, =
another co-working platform, pairs people with an online buddy who is requi=
red to be present and on screen, with the exception of bathroom breaks, to =
keep you from slacking.=C2=A0
Kathryn Stinson, a psychotherapist in St. Louis, hosts hourlong body-doubli=
ng sessions for Flow Club that start with five minutes devoted to sharing g=
oals, followed by a period of silent work while everyone is muted. In the F=
riday session attended by McKinsey and Grossman, Stinson asked what people =
accomplished at the end of the hour.=C2=A0

The optimal amount of meetings is not zero, even if you work alone.

 =20
   =20
      People who live in glass houses
   =20
 =20

Man, I have absolutely no idea:

Inside Tesla, it was known as =E2=80=9CProject 42,=E2=80=9D and the plans c=
alled for a dramatic glass-walled building to rise near the automaker=E2=80=
=99s headquarters outside this capital city.=C2=A0
Internally, the secret project was described as a house for Chief Executive=
=C2=A0Elon Musk.
One concept showed a structure in the shape of a twisted hexagon on waterfr=
ont land with Tesla=E2=80=99s factory in the background, according to a doc=
ument reviewed by The Wall Street Journal.=C2=A0
Other renderings depicted an expansive glass box, reminiscent of Apple=E2=
=80=99s store on Fifth Avenue in Manhattan, with a residential area that ap=
peared to include bedrooms, bathrooms and a kitchen, said people familiar w=
ith the matter. ...
Along the way, the project drew scrutiny from Tesla lawyers and board membe=
rs, according to people with knowledge of the situation. An order for milli=
ons of dollars in specialized glass=E2=80=94the type of large-format panels=
 used on building facades=E2=80=94sparked concern among some employees abou=
t what the materials would be used for, some of the people said.
After that order, Tesla board members investigated whether company resource=
s had been misused and if Musk, himself, had a role, some people with knowl=
edge of the situation said.

Look honestly I think spending millions of dollars to build a giant glass h=
ouse for Elon Musk right near Tesla headquarters is a good use of corporate=
 funds? Keep an eye on him. Really if the board had thought of this I would=
 be praising it as an innovative corporate governance idea.=C2=A0You can=E2=
=80=99t necessarily make Elon Musk warn you when he=E2=80=99s going to   tw=
eet something material or go buy another company to run full-time, but you=
=C2=A0can=C2=A0give him the gift of a glass house=C2=A0and get yourself a t=
elescope.
I assume that=C2=A0=E2=80=9C42=E2=80=9D is the Douglas Adams number, and th=
at originally they wanted to call it Project 69 but chickened out.

