<tr>
<td class=3D"body-component__content" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; m=
so-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt; line-height: 150%; padding: 0 =
10px;">
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">ESG Aramco</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If I tell you that Company X is an oil company=
, you probably assume that it creates a lot of carbon emissions. Drilling f=
or oil is dirty work, but also the ultimate=C2=A0<em>users=C2=A0</em>of the=
 oil will burn it and create a lot of emissions, and it seems reasonable to=
 attribute those emissions to Company X. If it didn=E2=80=99t drill the oil=
, they wouldn=E2=80=99t burn the oil. Maybe they would burn some other oil?=
 But that=E2=80=99s not the point. The point is that most people associate =
oil companies with carbon emissions, pretty reasonably. And so, for instanc=
e, environmental, social and governance-focused (ESG) investors might lower=
 the carbon impact of their portfolios by not investing in=C2=A0oil compani=
es.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If I tell you that Company Y is an investment =
firm, you <em>probably=C2=A0</em>assume that it does not itself do a lot of=
 carbon emissions. It=E2=80=99s some people, some desks, some computers. It=
 uses electricity, and its employees probably take business trips on airpla=
nes, but no more than most companies. If you care about carbon emissions, y=
ou=C2=A0might ask questions like =E2=80=9Cis Company Y an ESG investment fi=
rm?=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cdoes Company Y do a lot of investing in coal compa=
nies?=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cwhat are the total carbon emissions of the compa=
nies in Company Y=E2=80=99s portfolio?=E2=80=9D; you might want to get a br=
oader sense of Company Y=E2=80=99s contribution to carbon emissions beyond =
the amount of carbon that it uses in its own operations.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But you =E2=80=A6=C2=A0might =E2=80=A6=C2=A0no=
t? At some point the accounting has to stop. If you are, for instance, your=
self an ESG fund manager, and your mandate is to buy bonds of companies tha=
t don=E2=80=99t do a lot of carbon emissions and to avoid bonds of companie=
s that do do a lot of carbon emissions, you might have a simpler checklist.=
 Oil companies: bad, no, don=E2=80=99t buy their bonds. Investment firms: f=
ine, yes, not a problem, whether they are ESG investment firms or regular i=
nvestment firms or even coal-focused investment firms.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But investment firms are, in a sense, free. An=
 investment firm is a company whose business is owning securities; you can =
create companies easily,=C2=A0and you can turn anything into a security. Yo=
u can take a bunch of real assets =E2=80=94=C2=A0pipelines, oil wells, what=
ever =E2=80=94=C2=A0and put them into a company, and then that company can =
issue securities to another company, and=C2=A0that second<em>=C2=A0</em>com=
pany doesn=E2=80=99t own any pipelines or oil wells or whatever;=C2=A0<em>t=
hat=C2=A0</em>company just owns securities. It=E2=80=99s just an investment=
=C2=A0firm! Totally clean.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomber=
gbusiness.com/click/32060626.265406/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXd=
zL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDctMTEvc2F1ZGktYXJhbWNvLWdldHRpbmctY2FzaC1tZWFudC1mb3=
Itc3VzdGFpbmFibGUtaW52ZXN0bWVudC1yZXZlYWxzLWVzZy1sb29waG9sZT9jbXBpZD1CQkQwN=
zEyMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1=
dG1fdGVybT0yMzA3MTImdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23=
cBb0dbb31a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backg=
round-color: #ccc;">  a hilarious arbitrage</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Saudi Aramco, the world=E2=80=99s largest oil =
company, has become an unlikely beneficiary of funds earmarked for sustaina=
ble investments thanks to a complex web of financial structures it used to =
raise money from its pipelines.=C2=A0=E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The unlikely tie-up between Aramco and ESG beg=
an with the creation of two subsidiaries =E2=80=94 the Aramco Oil Pipelines=
 Company and the Aramco Gas Pipelines Company. Aramco sold 49% of the share=
s in each unit to consortiums led by EIG Global Energy Partners LLC and Bla=
ckRock Inc., respectively. These investors used bridge loans from banks to =
fund those transactions.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In order to generate cash to repay the bank lo=
ans, the EIG and BlackRock consortiums created two special purpose vehicles=
: EIG Pearl Holdings and GreenSaif Pipelines Bidco, both registered at the =
same Luxembourg address. These SPVs then sold bonds, which, since they had =
no direct links to the fossil-fuel industry, ended up getting an above-aver=
age score in a widely-used JPMorgan Chase &amp; Co. sustainability screenin=
g based on third-party ESG scores.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">From there, the bonds made their way into JPMo=
rgan=E2=80=99s ESG indexes, which are cumulatively tracked by about $40 bil=
lion of assets under management. Investors in the SPV bonds include funds m=
anaged by UBS Group AG, Legal &amp; General Investment Management and the i=
nvestment arm of HSBC Holdings Plc.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You can do this with anything! Absolutely anyt=
hing:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Horrible Coal Inc. wants to raise mone=
y.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">It sets up a special purpose ve=
hicle, Hypertechnical Investments Ltd.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5=
px;">Horrible Coal issues bonds to Hypertechnical Investments.</li>=09<li s=
tyle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Hypertechnical issues its own bonds to ESG fun=
ds: =E2=80=9CWe are just a little old investment firm, just two traders and=
 two computers, no carbon emissions here! And our credit is very good, beca=
use we have no other liabilities and our assets are all investment-grade bo=
nds. =E2=80=98Which investment-grade bonds,=E2=80=99 did you ask? Sorry, I=
=E2=80=99m not sure I heard you right, you=E2=80=99re breaking up. Anyway w=
e=E2=80=99ll look=C2=A0for your check, bye!=E2=80=9D</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Though my made-up names are silly, and in the =
actual Aramco case one of the not-an-oil-company=C2=A0SPVs is named =E2=80=
=9CGreenSaif=C2=A0Pipelines Bidco.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CPipelines=E2=80=9D is =
right in the name! The only way you would think that GreenSaif Pipelines Bi=
dco =E2=80=9Chad no direct links to the fossil-fuel industry=E2=80=9D is if=
 (1) you started reading the name but stopped after you got to the =E2=80=
=9CGreen=E2=80=9D part (plausible!) or (2) you never read the name at all, =
never thought about it, just looked at the balance sheet and saw only share=
s of stock, not pipelines or oil wells, and said =E2=80=9Cah, stock, well, =
that=E2=80=99s green enough.=E2=80=9D</p>
