9a23cBf76fa2d0" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_b=
lank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; b=
ackground-color: #ccc;">  John Authers explains</a>, but it has the=C2=A0<e=
m>purpose=C2=A0</em>of helping index funds linked to the Nasdaq 100 be in c=
ompliance with US Securities and Exchange Commission and Internal Revenue S=
ervice rules about diversification. Those rules basically require funds to =
have no more than 50% of their assets in stocks that each make up more than=
 5% of their assets; currently the Nasdaq 100 is somewhat uncomfortably clo=
se to that cap, so it is going to lower the weights of its biggest stocks t=
o give index funds more breathing room.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is Nasdaq=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://li=
nk.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32060626.265406/aHR0cHM6Ly9pbmRleGVzLm5=
hc2RhcS5jb20vZG9jcy9NZXRob2RvbG9neV9ORFgucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8985=
d551" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" styl=
e=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width:=
 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-=
color: #ccc;"> published methodology</a> for re-weighting the Nasdaq 100. B=
asically the method is:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Weight the stocks in the index by mar=
ket capitalization to get initial weights.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-botto=
m: 5px;">=E2=80=9CIf the aggregate weight of the subset of issuers whose St=
age 1 weights exceed 4.5% does not exceed 48%, Stage 1 weights are used as =
final weights.=E2=80=9D If not, then =E2=80=9Cthe aggregate weight of the s=
ubset of issuers whose Stage 1 weights exceed 4.5% is set to 40%.=E2=80=9D=
=C2=A0</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This has a curious little effect. If the stock=
s with greater-than-4.5% initial weights add up to=C2=A0significantly<em>=
=C2=A0</em>more than 40%, they will all be cut back a lot<a class=3D"footno=
te-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: no=
ne !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bord=
er-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important;=
 display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>: If there are 10 stocks that would each make up 6% of the index by mar=
ket cap (60% total), then this method would cut them each back by one-third=
, to 4% each (40% total, the Stage 2 cap). And this would mean that stocks =
with less-than-4.5% initial weights would be <em>increased</em> significant=
ly: If the 10 big stocks get cut back from 60% of the index to 40%, then th=
e 90 smaller stocks each have to have their weights go up by 50% (from 40% =
total to 60%) to make up for it.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If each of those 90 small stocks made up 0.44%=
 of the index by market cap, they=E2=80=99d each increase to 0.66% as the b=
ig stocks got cut back. But if <em>one </em>of those small stocks made up, =
say, 4.49% of the index by market cap, then I=C2=A0<em>think=C2=A0</em>that=
 its weighting would also increase, in Stage 2, to about 6.7% of the index.=
 This seems kind of=C2=A0<em>wrong=C2=A0</em>=E2=80=94=C2=A0it sort of defe=
ats the purpose of the adjustment<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footn=
ote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bo=
ttom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !i=
mportant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;"=
>
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0and perhaps Nasdaq would avoid it, by capping the =
Stage 2 weights rather than doing everything pro rata. But the methodology =
does seem to suggest that the weighting of almost-but-not-quite 4.5% stocks=
 would go up in the adjustment, possibly to above 5%.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This would mean that, in this adjustment, a st=
ock that is just more than 4.5% of the market capitalization of the Nasdaq =
100 would lose a lot of weight in the index, while a stock that is just les=
s than 4.5% would gain a lot of weight in the index.</p>
