: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bord=
er-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #cc=
c;">  kind of cool I guess</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Time is money, and Shopify Inc. wants its work=
ers to understand that maxim applies to pointless meetings, too.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Canadian e-commerce company has rolled out=
 a calculator embedded in employees=E2=80=99 calendar app that estimates th=
e cost of any meeting with three or more people. The tool uses average comp=
ensation data across roles and disciplines, along with meeting length and a=
ttendee count, to put a price tag on the event. A typical 30 minute endeavo=
r with three employees can run from $700 up to $1,600. Adding an executive =
=E2=80=94 like Chief Operating Officer Kaz Nejatian, who built the program =
during a company-wide hack day =E2=80=94 can shoot the cost above $2,000. .=
..</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CNo one at Shopify would expense a $50=
0 dinner,=E2=80=9D Nejatian said in an interview. =E2=80=9CBut lots and lot=
s of people spend way more than that in meetings without ever making a deci=
sion. The goal of this thing is to show you that time is money. If you have=
 to spend it, you think about it.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You can take that too literally, though. Nothi=
ng you do at work is free,=C2=A0everything has a time cost, and most people=
 cannot spend 40 hours a week shipping impeccable products. If you quantify=
 the time cost of meetings, you will get fewer meetings, but if you quantif=
y=C2=A0<em>only=C2=A0</em>the time cost of meetings and not of anything els=
e, you might=C2=A0get a below-optimal amount of meetings, as people replace=
 expensive-seeming meetings with free-seeming substitutes. If meetings are =
expensive but emails are free, some conversations that should be meetings w=
ill be interminable email threads.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One=C2=A0funny solution would be embedding the=
 cost calculator in=C2=A0<em>all=C2=A0</em>of the employees=E2=80=99 apps, =
not just the calendar one.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-8" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !importan=
t; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[8]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Write an email and the cost of your time ticks up every second. R=
ead Money Stuff on your browser with a little price tag next to it increasi=
ng every second. Slack Nejatian and get a bill for it. Call him on the phon=
e, get a bill. At the next hack day, you build an artificial-intelligence t=
ool to estimate the most cost-effective way to discuss anything, given the =
subject matter and the people involved, so you can choose between meetings =
and emails and Slacks and phone calls in a way that minimizes your bill.</p=
>
